<hr> <heading1><a href="http://www.stayorswitch.com/blog/blowin-in-the-wind/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Blowin&#8217; in the wind">Blowin&#8217; in the wind</a></heading1></br>
<heading4>November 14th, 2015</heading4>
<p><p><a href="http://stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Screen-Shot-2015-11-12-at-10.23.01-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-152" src="http://stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Screen-Shot-2015-11-12-at-10.23.01-PM-300x198.png" alt="Field of Corn" width="300" height="198" srcset="http://www.stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Screen-Shot-2015-11-12-at-10.23.01-PM-300x198.png 300w, http://www.stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Screen-Shot-2015-11-12-at-10.23.01-PM.png 640w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a></p>
<p>My brother recently wrote a <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://lifeandwildlife.com/2015/11/11/are-gmos-a-bfd/">blog post about GMOs</a></span> on his science blog and it got me thinking about patented seeds blowing from one field to another.</p>
<p>Imagine you farm a 100&#215;100 yard square field with another 100&#215;100 yard square field directly to your east. The field to your east has patented seeds and you&#8217;re worried about the seeds getting blown into your field. The wind is blowing from the northeast and carries a seed about 50 yards. If 9 seeds are released randomly from plants in your neighbor&#8217;s field today, what&#8217;s the probability that at least one of the seeds blows into your field?</p>

<div class='easySpoilerWrapper' style='border-color:#7c7c7c;'>
<table class='easySpoilerTable' border='0' style='text-align:center;' align='center' bgcolor='FFFFFF' >

<tr style='white-space:normal;'>
<th class='easySpoilerTitleA' style='white-space:normal;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;vertical-align:middle;font-size:100%;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c;color:#f4f4f4;'><a href='blog' onclick='wpSpoilerToggle("spoilerDiv3ce08003",true,"Show Solution","Hide Solution","fast",false); return false;' onselectstart='return false;' style='text-decoration: none;color:#f4f4f4;'>Show/Hide Solution</a></th>
<th class='easySpoilerTitleB'style='padding:0px;text-align:right;vertical-align:middle;font-size:100%;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c; white-space:nowrap;'><a href='blog'  class='easySpoilerButton' style='font-size:100%;color:#f4f4f4;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border: 1px inset;border-style:solid;border-color:#7c7c7c;display:none; margin: 3px 0px 3px; padding: 4px; ' align='right'>Select</a><a href='blog'  id='spoilerDiv3ce08003_action' class='easySpoilerButtonBare' value="Show Solution" align='right' style='font-size:100%;color:#f4f4f4;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border: 1px inset;border-style:solid;border-color:#7c7c7c;display:none; margin: 3px 0px 3px 5px; padding: 4px;'>Show Solution</></th>
</tr>
<tr><td class='easySpoilerRow' colspan='2' style='border-color:#7c7c7c;'><div id='spoilerDiv3ce08003' class='easySpoilerSpoils'  style='display:none; white-space:wrap; overflow:auto; vertical-align:middle;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;color:#f4f4f4;border-color:#7c7c7c;'>
 The short answer is that there&#8217;s a 90.3% chance that at least one of the seeds blows into your field. The diagram below shows region A. If a seed originates from this region, it will end up in your field.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="http://stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Probability-Problem-Diagram-Patented-Seeds-3.png"><img class="alignleft wp-image-164 " src="http://stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Probability-Problem-Diagram-Patented-Seeds-3.png" alt="Probability Problem Diagram - Patented Seeds (3)" width="710" height="532" srcset="http://www.stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Probability-Problem-Diagram-Patented-Seeds-3.png 960w, http://www.stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Probability-Problem-Diagram-Patented-Seeds-3-300x225.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 710px) 100vw, 710px" /></a></p>
<p>
</div></td></tr>
</table>
<div class='easySpoilerConclude' style='border-color:#7c7c7c;'><table class='easySpoilerTable' border='0' style='text-align:center;' frame='box' align='center' bgcolor='FFFFFF'><tr><th class='easySpoilerEnd' style='width:100%;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c;'></th><td class='easySpoilerEnd' style='white-space:nowrap;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c;' colspan='2'></td></tr><tr><td class='easySpoilerGroupWrapperLastRow' colspan='2' style='background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c;'></td></tr></table></div>
</div>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
</p>
<hr> <heading1><a href="http://www.stayorswitch.com/blog/travel-coincidence/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to True Story: Travel Coincidence!">True Story: Travel Coincidence!</a></heading1></br>
<heading4>October 26th, 2015</heading4>
<p><p><a href="http://stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/airplane-698539_1920.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-144" src="http://stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/airplane-698539_1920-300x199.jpg" alt="Airplane Seats" width="300" height="199" srcset="http://www.stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/airplane-698539_1920-300x199.jpg 300w, http://www.stayorswitch.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/airplane-698539_1920-1024x680.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a></p>
<p>It&#8217;s been a while since the last post. Here&#8217;s a situation that actually happened last weekend. My wife and I were flying home from a wedding and the first leg of our itinerary was by chance the same as the first leg of the itinerary of my wife&#8217;s sister, who lives in a different state. So, we were going to be on the same plane.</p>
<p>When we got on the plane, which had 12 rows with two seats on either side of the aisle, my wife&#8217;s sister was across the aisle from us in the same row! This whole circumstance occurred completely by chance. Since a lot of information needs to be collected to calculate the probability that we were on the same flight, we&#8217;ll take that as a given. Given that we were on the same flight, what is the probability that we were sitting next to each other on the flight? Assume that my wife and I will book two seats on the same side of the aisle and my wife&#8217;s sister will book an aisle seat.</p>

<div class='easySpoilerWrapper' style='border-color:#7c7c7c;'>
<table class='easySpoilerTable' border='0' style='text-align:center;' align='center' bgcolor='FFFFFF' >

<tr style='white-space:normal;'>
<th class='easySpoilerTitleA' style='white-space:normal;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;vertical-align:middle;font-size:100%;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c;color:#f4f4f4;'><a href='blog' onclick='wpSpoilerToggle("spoilerDiv33e98004",true,"Show Solution","Hide Solution","fast",false); return false;' onselectstart='return false;' style='text-decoration: none;color:#f4f4f4;'>Show/Hide Solution</a></th>
<th class='easySpoilerTitleB'style='padding:0px;text-align:right;vertical-align:middle;font-size:100%;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c; white-space:nowrap;'><a href='blog'  class='easySpoilerButton' style='font-size:100%;color:#f4f4f4;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border: 1px inset;border-style:solid;border-color:#7c7c7c;display:none; margin: 3px 0px 3px; padding: 4px; ' align='right'>Select</a><a href='blog'  id='spoilerDiv33e98004_action' class='easySpoilerButtonBare' value="Show Solution" align='right' style='font-size:100%;color:#f4f4f4;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border: 1px inset;border-style:solid;border-color:#7c7c7c;display:none; margin: 3px 0px 3px 5px; padding: 4px;'>Show Solution</></th>
</tr>
<tr><td class='easySpoilerRow' colspan='2' style='border-color:#7c7c7c;'><div id='spoilerDiv33e98004' class='easySpoilerSpoils'  style='display:none; white-space:wrap; overflow:auto; vertical-align:middle;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;color:#f4f4f4;border-color:#7c7c7c;'>
 As is true with many probability problems, it&#8217;s helpful to break it into two distinct events: (1) we select our seats and (2) my wife&#8217;s sister selects her seat. We can choose our two seats anywhere, lets say 10A and 10B. At this point, there are 23 remaining aisle seats (12 rows * 2 aisle seats per row &#8211; 1 aisle seat that we have). One of those 23 aisle seats is across the aisle from us. So the probability that she&#8217;s sitting next to us is 1/23.</p>
<p>Another variation would allow for my wife&#8217;s sister to choose from window seats as well. In this case there are 46 remaining seats after we choose our 2 seats and only one of those is the aisle seat across from us. So that would yield a probability of 1/46. I&#8217;ll have to ask my wife&#8217;s sister if she chose an aisle seat intentionally or if it was assigned to her!<br />

</div></td></tr>
</table>
<div class='easySpoilerConclude' style='border-color:#7c7c7c;'><table class='easySpoilerTable' border='0' style='text-align:center;' frame='box' align='center' bgcolor='FFFFFF'><tr><th class='easySpoilerEnd' style='width:100%;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c;'></th><td class='easySpoilerEnd' style='white-space:nowrap;background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c;' colspan='2'></td></tr><tr><td class='easySpoilerGroupWrapperLastRow' colspan='2' style='background-color:#7c7c7c;background-image:none;border-color:#7c7c7c;'></td></tr></table></div>
</div>

